Systemic rheumatic disorders		 Pleuroparenchymal fibroelastosis

  • Main route is percutaneous inoculation. Inhalation and ingestion also possible.
  • Tranmission may be through the inhaled route as well.
  • Person to person transmission is extremely rare.
  • Mother to baby transmission via breast feeding can occur due to mastitis.
  • P-incu = 1 week (4-9 days, max 21)
  • Can present as reactivation of latent infection years after exposure
  • Exposure to soil and water.
  • Wide spectrum of disease:
    • acute or chronic
    • localized or disseminated (septicaemic melioidosis has high mortality)
      Severe infection is rare in healthy adults. Most infections are asymptomatic.

Paroxysmal cold haemoglobinuria

  • Also called Donath-Landsteiner anaemia.
  • Caused by IgG. (usually IgG causes warm AIHA)
  • It is a biphasic antibody which binds in the cold (peripheries) and causes lysis when rewarmed.
  • Mainly occurs in children but can occur in adults with tertiary syphillis or haematologic malignancies.
  • Source

DVT (Deep vein thrombosis)

  1. -More than one episode of unprovoked proximal DVT or symptomatic PE -> indefinite anticoagulation
  2. -For most patients with a first episode of unprovoked proximal DVT and/or symptomatic PE -> indefinite anticoagulation.
  3. -Patients with active cancer -> may need indefinite anticoagulation (compare with risk of bleeding)

Myelodysplastic syndromes

  • Commonly found in aging population
  • All are characterized by one or more peripheral blood cytopenias.
  • Bone marrow is usually hypercellular, but rarely hypocellular.
  • High risk of progression to [[Haematologic malignancies-Summary#Acute myeloid leukemia#AML]]
  • Bone marrow cells display aberrant morphology and maturation (dysmyelopoiesis), resulting in ineffective blood cell production.
  • usually cause macrocytic anaemias.

#2023GM/Q21

Causative organisms

  • 80% of SA in healthy individuals is caused by Gram +ve organisms (Staph. aureus - 60% and non group A strep - 15%; Strep pneumoniae - 3%).

  • Disseminated gonococcal infection can present with oligoarthirits

  • Septic patients (especially those with damaged joins due to RA) can develop oligoarthritis

    • IV drug users have axial joint involvement.

Treatment:

IV antibiotics for 2 weeks; Oral for further 4 weeks.

  • Empirical therapy: vancomycin + clindamycin / cephalosporins -> as aureus is commonest.

  • If Gram negative suspected -> cephalosporins + cipro

  • Joint washout must be done in all cases.

If prosthesis is involved -> two stage treatment and very long treatment;

  • Remove prosthesis - then antibiotics.
  • Then replace prosthesis.
  • Followed by 2-6 weeks of IV antibiotics and then 3 - 6 months of oral antibiotics.

see [[2022-SBR-MAY#Gonococcal arthritis|Gonococcal Arthritis]]

Tuberculous arthritis

  • 1% of TB patients develop the complication.
  • Insidious onset.
  • TB invades synovium or intervertebral disc.
  • Caseating granulomas
  • Rapid destruction of involved joint.
  • TB most commonly affects spine (50%) -> hip -> Knee -> Ribs
  • Treatment is for 9 months.

Meningococcal arthritis

  • It's a complication of meningococcal septicaemia
  • caused by immune complex deposition -> joint culture is sterile.

#2017GM-APR/Q16

[!INFO] Intermediate syndrome
- Ten to 40 percent of patients poisoned with organophosphorus develop a distinct neurologic disorder 24 to 96 hours after exposure and resolution of cholinergic excess.
- Mainly Proximal Muscle weakness: characteristic neurological findings including neck flexion weakness, decreased deep tendon reflexes, cranial nerve abnormalities, proximal muscle weakness, and respiratory insufficiency
- Thought to result from dysfunction of the nicotinic receptors due to prolonged activation.
- Complete resolution occurs in 2-3 weeks if the patient receives ventilatory support

[!INFO] Polyneuropathy
Several weeks after exposure
Axonal neuropathy
Characterized by distal weakness and sensory loss
